Overview: The Daboku, first appearing at the tail end of the Succession Wars, was a prime example of trying to improve on an already effective design. Made to mimic the combat role of the Awesome assault 'Mech, the Daboku was to use a wide mix of weaponry and certain pieces of newly-rediscovered technology to create a new premier assault 'Mech for the DCMS. Unfortunately, Luthien Armor Works and the Daboku's design committee grossly dropped the ball. While the Daboku could engage at ranges beyond many other Assault 'Mechs, its firepower was minimal and the design itself was plagued with technical problems. Ammunition jams, heat management issues, short-circuits-all were minimal compared to the miswired CASE sensors that would often trigger the auto eject sequence with only a single impact on the right armor panel.

Capabilities: The long range of the Daboku is both its defining feature and its saving grace. Slow, underarmored, and prone to overheating, any enemy BattleMechs able to close with the Daboku often found it easy to dispatch. MechWarriors of every origin despised the design, with few able to use the Daboku to accomplish the tasks expected of a 90-ton machine.

Deployment: As an in-house design, House Kurita was the sole manufacturer and user of the design at its inception. The War of 3039 saw many Daboku spread to the Combine's two main foes, with MechWarriors from the Federated Commonwealth often salvaging the design. It was a small measure of revenge that Kuritan samurai could exploit the same weakness that had lost them so many 'Mechs, quickly using the CASE sensor flaw against any MechWarriors fielding captured Dabokus. The Daboku, due to its many problems, quickly fell out of favor. None remained by the FedCom Civil War, and the design itself was quickly supplanted by the much more effective Mauler.

# Fluff Date: 2026-02-11 15:11:17
overview:<p>The Daboku was born from Project Daboku in 3036, when Luthien Armor Works assembled a think tank of senior DCMS officers, scientists, and researchers to examine Star League technology recovered from the Helm Memory Core. Tasked by the Coordinator with producing tangible results from these rediscovered technologies, the politically fractured group settled on designing a new assault 'Mech, a ninety-ton ranged-combat platform modeled after IBMU's venerable Awesome. The project was handed to LAW based on their recent success with the Hatamoto series, and the design drew heavily from an earlier Capellan prototype that the Combine had acquired through backchannels.</p><p>The Daboku debuted in 3038 to almost immediate ridicule from DCMS pilots. A short production run of approximately three hundred units rolled off the New Samarkand line before Luthien Armor Works closed and retooled the facility, driven by an avalanche of detailed deficiency reports from the field.</p>

capabilities:<p>Conceived as a long-range gunnery platform, the Daboku mounted dual Tronel large lasers paired with Holly LRM racks and four Imperator Smoothie-2 autocannons, giving it the theoretical ability to engage targets well beyond conventional engagement ranges. In practice, nearly every major system suffered from critical design flaws. The weapons were chronically underpowered and prone to excessive overheating due to an inadequate number of heat sinks. The frame itself was too compact to properly handle the autocannons' multiple ammunition feeds, resulting in constant jamming, while the Holly loading mechanisms proved equally unreliable.</p><p>The Tronel lasers presented their own problems, as design incompatibilities prevented the mounting of adequate heat baffles on the charging mechanisms. The resulting thermal buildup frequently short-circuited the Matabushi targeting system. Most critically, the newly rediscovered CASE technology was improperly installed in virtually every unit produced. Rather than properly re-engineering the system for the Daboku's specific chassis, LAW technicians essentially copied the technology from salvaged Star League 'Mechs without the necessary calibration. This resulted in the CASE sending false catastrophic ammunition signals when the lower center torso armor absorbed kinetic impacts, triggering the auto-eject system and launching pilots skyward, often during routine training exercises with inert rounds.</p>

deployment:<p>No factory variants of the Daboku were ever produced. The sole DCMS-MX90-D model represents the only configuration to reach the field, with its litany of design flaws ensuring the line was shuttered after a production run of roughly three hundred units. The chassis would ultimately be refined and redesigned through the 3040s as Luthien Armor Works gained a proper understanding of Star League technology, with the successful result reintroduced under the Mauler designation to deliberately distance the new production model from the Daboku's notorious reputation.</p>

history:<p>The Daboku's origins trace to the Draconis Combine's efforts to exploit the Helm Memory Core, recovered by the Free Worlds League in 3028 and subsequently disseminated across the Inner Sphere. In 3036, a politically charged think tank was assembled under the Coordinator's authority, drawing from DCMS officers, Luthien Armor Works engineers, university researchers, and graduate students. The group was directed to apply newly rediscovered Star League-era technologies to an existing chassis, Project Nainokami, a Capellan 'Mech design that Earthwerks had sold to the Combine after abandoning it in the prototype stage.</p><p>The resulting Daboku debuted in 3038 and was almost immediately recognized as a failure. The design attempted to replicate the Awesome's long-range fire support role but with an entirely different weapons mix and system construction that the Alshain chassis could not properly support. A short test run of three hundred units was produced at LAW's New Samarkand facility before the production line was closed down and retooled. Pilots made exhaustive efforts to catalog every flaw, submitting debriefing reports that often ran to several pages of detailed technical criticisms.</p><p>Despite its known deficiencies, the Daboku was rushed to frontline units along the Federated Suns border just in time for the War of 3039. DCMS pilots were largely uninformed of the CASE system's critical flaws, and many Dabokus were lost not to enemy fire but to their own malfunctioning ejection systems. Moderate armor damage to the lower torso (damage that would be inconsequential on most assault 'Mechs) triggered the auto-eject sequence, sending pilots rocketing into the sky at the worst possible moments. When the scope of the problem became apparent, surviving MechWarriors attempted to disable the auto-eject entirely, gambling that the CASE's passive blast containment alone would provide sufficient protection.</p><p>The Armed Forces of the Federated Suns capitalized on these early losses, recovering numerous Dabokus as salvage. Several were redeployed with Lyran Commonwealth Armed Forces units along the Combine border, where DCMS warriors discovered they could exploit the same ejection vulnerability against their former machines by targeting the lower center torso. The Lyrans adapted quickly, and most salvaged Dabokus were ultimately stripped for spare parts to support other assault designs rather than risk fielding them in combat.</p><p>By the war's end, the DCMS had shelved the design entirely. When Luthien Armor Works revisited the project in the 3040s with a far more mature understanding of Star League technology, the accumulated engineering data from the Daboku's failures proved invaluable in rectifying the design's systemic flaws. The successful result was reintroduced as the MAL-1R Mauler, with the new designation chosen deliberately to bury the Daboku name and its association with one of the most spectacularly flawed assault 'Mechs to emerge from the late Succession Wars era.</p>

